# 🧪 Experiment–2  
# Common Source Amplifier – Three Source Configurations  

**Technology:** 180nm CMOS  
**Tool Used:** LTspice  

---

## 🔷 Given Specifications (Common for A, B, C)

| Parameter | Value |
|------------|--------|
| VDD | 1.8 V |
| Target Drain Current (ID) | 200 µA |
| Overdrive Voltage (Vov) | 0.25 V |
| NMOS Vth | 0.36 V |
| PMOS Vth | 0.39 V |
| Channel Length | 180 nm |
| Power Limit | ≤ 0.5 mW |

---

# 🔴 Circuit A  
## Common Source Amplifier with Source Resistor (Rs)

---

### 1️⃣ DC Bias Design

**NMOS Gate Voltage**

VGS = Vth + Vov  
VGS = 0.36 + 0.25  
VGS = 0.61 V  

Assume source voltage drop:

VRS = 0.2 V  

RS = VRS / ID  
RS = 0.2 / 200µA  
RS = 1 kΩ  

Gate bias voltage:

VB1 = VGS + VRS  
VB1 = 0.61 + 0.2  
VB1 = 0.81 V  

**PMOS Bias**

VSG = |Vthp| + Vov  
VSG = 0.39 + 0.25  
VSG = 0.64 V  

VB2 = VDD – VSG  
VB2 = 1.8 – 0.64  
VB2 = 1.16 V  

---

### 2️⃣ Saturation Verification

NMOS:  
VDS ≈ 0.83 V  
0.83 > 0.25 ✔  

PMOS:  
VSD ≈ 0.76 V  
0.76 > 0.25 ✔  

Both transistors operate in saturation.

---

### 3️⃣ Small Signal Parameters

gm = 2ID / Vov  
gm = 2 × 200µ / 0.25  
gm = 1.6 mS  

Assume λ = 0.1 V⁻¹  

ro = 1 / (λID)  
ro = 1 / (0.1 × 200µ)  
ro = 50 kΩ  

ro(total) = ro || ro  
ro(total) = 25 kΩ  

---

### 4️⃣ Theoretical Gain

Av = -gm(ro||ro) / (1 + gmRS)

Numerator:  
1.6m × 25k = 40  

Denominator:  
1 + (1.6 × 1k × 10⁻³)  
= 1 + 1.6  
= 2.6  

Av ≈ 15.38 V/V  

Gain(dB) = 20 log(15.38)  
Gain ≈ 23.73 dB  

---

### 5️⃣ Practical Gain (Simulation)

Vin ≈ 20 mV  
Vout ≈ 240 mV  

Av ≈ 12 V/V  
Gain ≈ 21.5 dB  

---

### 6️⃣ Power Verification

P = VDD × ID  
P = 1.8 × 200µ  
P = 0.36 mW ✔  

---

### 🔎 Observation

• Source degeneration reduces gain  
• Improved linearity  
• Stable bias  

---

# 🔵 Circuit B  
## CS Amplifier with NMOS Current Source

---

### 1️⃣ DC Design

Current source sets ID ≈ 200 µA  

VB1 ≈ 0.61 V  
VB2 ≈ 1.16 V  

No physical Rs → degeneration due to finite output resistance of current source  

---

### 2️⃣ Saturation Check

Current source NMOS: VDS > Vov ✔  
Amplifier NMOS: VDS > 0.25 ✔  
PMOS: VSD > 0.25 ✔  

All devices in saturation.

---

### 3️⃣ Small Signal Insight

Effective degeneration:  
Reff ≈ 1/gm3  

Voltage gain:

Av = -gm(ro||ro) / (1 + gm/gm3)

If gm3 ≈ gm:  
Denominator ≈ 2  
Av ≈ 40 / 2  
Av ≈ 20 V/V (ideal case)

Practical gain is lower due to non-ideal effects.

---

### 4️⃣ Simulation Results

| Parameter | Value |
|------------|--------|
| Gain | 2.45 V/V |
| Gain (dB) | 7.78 dB |
| Bandwidth | 42 MHz |
| Gain Bandwidth Product | 104 MHz |

---

### 🔎 Observation

• Best bias stability  
• Strong degeneration  
• Lowest gain  

---

# 🟢 Circuit C  
## CS Amplifier with Diode-Connected NMOS

---

### 1️⃣ DC Design

Diode NMOS ensures:

VDS = VGS  

Self-biased current control  
ID ≈ 200 µA  

---

### 2️⃣ Saturation Verification

All devices satisfy VDS > Vov ✔  
Saturation maintained ✔  

---

### 3️⃣ Small Signal Model

Diode transistor introduces:

Rd ≈ 1/gm  

Less degeneration than Circuit B → Higher gain.

---

### 4️⃣ Theoretical Gain

Av ≈ -gm(ro||ro)  
Av = 1.6m × 25k  
Av = 40 V/V  

Gain(dB) = 20 log(40)  
Gain ≈ 32 dB  

---

### 5️⃣ Simulation Results

| Parameter | Value |
|------------|--------|
| Gain | 25.05 V/V |
| Gain (dB) | 27.97 dB |
| Bandwidth | 83.21 MHz |
| Gain Bandwidth Product | 2.08 GHz |

---

### 🔎 Observation

• Highest practical gain  
• Best bandwidth  
• Reduced degeneration  

---

# 📊 Final Comparison

| Parameter | Circuit A | Circuit B | Circuit C |
|------------|------------|------------|------------|
| Source Element | Rs | Current Source | Diode NMOS |
| Gain (V/V) | ~12 | 2.45 | 25.05 |
| Gain (dB) | 21.5 | 7.78 | 27.97 |
| Bandwidth | Moderate | Moderate | Highest |
| Power | 0.36 mW | 0.36 mW | 0.36 mW |

---

# 📚 Key Learnings

• Source degeneration reduces voltage gain  
• Current source improves bias stability  
• Diode configuration increases gain  
• Active load increases output resistance  
• Theoretical ≠ Practical due to:
  - Channel length modulation  
  - Parasitic capacitances  
  - Mobility degradation  
  - Short channel effects  

---

# 🏁 Final Conclusion

Three Common Source amplifier configurations were designed and simulated in 180nm CMOS.

Circuit A → Balanced performance  
Circuit B → Best bias stability but lowest gain  
Circuit C → Highest gain and bandwidth  

Source implementation significantly affects voltage gain and frequency response in CMOS analog design.
